WEBVTT

00:00.031 --> 00:02.697
Now, what do these people say?

00:02.737 --> 00:09.651
They say, this procedure often suffers from exploiting inaccuracies of the learned model.

00:10.733 --> 00:11.355
What does that mean?

00:11.856 --> 00:16.285
That basically means that if I have a world model and it is not accurate,

00:16.265 --> 00:29.419
then it is basically the thing that tries to find the best green path here, the optimizer, is sort of trying to find the best path against this world model.

00:30.059 --> 00:34.844
Now, if that world model is inaccurate, that can lead to devastating consequences.

00:35.005 --> 00:36.046
So what do we mean by this?

00:37.207 --> 00:38.068
I'll give you an example.

00:38.969 --> 00:41.091
If you have a room, right,

00:41.071 --> 00:51.106
And the room is, let's take our classic room like this, and you are here and you would like to go here.

00:52.188 --> 00:54.611
And so you're a reinforcement learning agent.

00:54.651 --> 00:56.314
You do some exploration, right?

00:56.374 --> 00:58.116
You explore a bit here.

00:58.176 --> 01:01.602
The next episode, you might go here and you might go here and so on.

01:01.642 --> 01:06.589
And over time, in this framework, you're going to build a model of the world.

01:06.569 --> 01:09.475
At the beginning, we won't tell you how these rooms look.

01:09.495 --> 01:11.119
You have to discover it by yourself.

01:11.520 --> 01:15.548
So maybe at the beginning, we only tell you there's these four walls.

01:15.648 --> 01:16.811
The rest you have to figure out.

01:17.332 --> 01:20.298
So on and on, you're going to fill in your blanks.

01:20.338 --> 01:24.848
You do your first explorations and you thought, there's a bit of a wall here, right?

01:24.828 --> 01:26.973
And there might be some wall here.

01:27.054 --> 01:28.337
I crashed into that, right?

01:28.357 --> 01:33.610
You go into here, you crash into a wall, you say, ah, there's a wall here and here, ah, there's a wall here.

01:33.770 --> 01:34.612
You go maybe here.

01:35.073 --> 01:35.996
Oh, there's no wall.

01:36.036 --> 01:36.978
So you go further.

01:37.038 --> 01:38.883
There's no wall anywhere here.

01:38.943 --> 01:39.785
You crash here.

01:39.905 --> 01:41.790
Okay, we already knew there's a wall.

01:41.770 --> 01:43.051
Maybe you crash here.

01:43.953 --> 01:44.233
All right.

01:44.293 --> 01:46.876
So right now you have, okay, you go here.

01:47.196 --> 01:52.723
You have a model of the world in this situation where there's a wall here, a wall down.

01:53.644 --> 01:59.851
And if you now try to do trajectory optimization, remember you have to go from here to here.

01:59.891 --> 02:04.336
If you try to do trajectory optimization, what is it going to turn out?

02:04.576 --> 02:06.799
It's going to turn out like, look.

02:06.779 --> 02:07.541
There you go.

02:07.581 --> 02:09.505
That works just fine.

02:10.286 --> 02:13.332
And that's not because you're so good at planning.

02:13.493 --> 02:27.201
I mean, you are good at planning, but because your model is inaccurate here, because it has never seen this, your entire training distribution that you trained the world model on only explored the area over here.

02:27.181 --> 02:51.450
So you see how the more efficient this planning algorithm is, like the blue arrow, the thing that finds the blue arrow, the more efficient that is, the more consequential it is when your learned world model has mistakes because it will exactly exploit these mistakes in order to get the shortest path possible or the highest reward in that case.

02:51.430 --> 02:59.500
And they call this like almost an adversarial attack on the world model, which is a pretty good way of framing it.

